\section{Markdown}
\label{sec:orgheadline32}
\begin{quote}
Markdown is a text-to-HTML conversion tool for web writers.\\
Markdown allows you to write using an easy-to-read, easy-to-write
plain text format, then convert it to structurally valid XHTML (or
HTML).
\end{quote}

\begin{itemize}
\item \href{https://daringfireball.net/projects/markdown/}{markdown}
\end{itemize}

\subsection{Markdown syntax}
\label{sec:orgheadline27}
\begin{itemize}
\item \href{https://daringfireball.net/projects/markdown/syntax}{markdown syntax}
\end{itemize}

\subsection{The Markdown file extension}
\label{sec:orgheadline28}
John Gruber didn't designated a file extension when he invented Markdown

\begin{quote}
John Gruber\\
The only file extension I would endorse is “.markdown” (I personally
use “.text” for my own files, and have BBEdit set to use Markdown
syntax coloring for that extension, which is why I never saw a need to
endorse an official extension.)
\end{quote}

\subsection{Different Markdown file extension}
\label{sec:orgheadline31}
\begin{itemize}
\item markdown
\item mdown
\item mkdn
\item md
\item mkd
\item mdwn
\item mdtxt
\item mdtext
\item text
\end{itemize}

\subsubsection{Markdown extensions used by different editors}
\label{sec:orgheadline30}
\begin{itemize}
\item GitHub: markdown, mdown, mkdn, mkd, md (source)
\item Elements Markdown Editor: markdown, mdown, mdwn, md
\item Vim markdown: markdown, mdown, mkdn, mdwn, mkd, md
\item Bitbucket: markdown, mdown, mkdn, mkd, md, text (source)
\end{itemize}

\begin{enumerate}
\item Markdown wikipedia article
\label{sec:orgheadline29}
\begin{itemize}
\item \href{https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Markdown}{markdown wikipedia}
\end{itemize}
\end{enumerate}

